"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating dynamic access tracking**\\\\n\\\\nI'm reflecting on whether a failing load in ClassLoader#loadClass counts as dynamic access. I wonder if the trace agent captures events before and after the loading process. If a load fails, it's likely that no configuration is emitted since the class wasn't loaded in the first place. This leaves me questioning how dynamic access is reported when it comes to errors in loading classes. It seems there's a lot to consider in this scenario!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering class issues**\\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking about potential context overloads and the expected outcomes. There might be an issue with the support class not being public, which could cause `ClassLoader.loadClass` for the implementation to fail. But do we really need it public? I think it would be better if I edited the setup and removed the support directory altogether. That could simplify things and make the process smoother, right? Let’s go for it.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_FD1viwqQ2CoeYvjh2VQexZyp|fc_0eb0aa1354b923450169fe44aed0f081919d08e49713ca52b4\", \"name\": \"edit\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/org.glassfish.jaxb/jaxb-xjc/4.0.6/src/test/java/org_glassfish_jaxb/jaxb_xjc/JAXBContextFactoryTest.java\", \"edits\": [{\"oldText\": \"import static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThatThrownBy;\\n\\nimport java.util.Map;\\n\", \"newText\": \"import static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThatExceptionOfType;\\n\\nimport java.util.Map;\\n\"}, {\"oldText\": \"import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\\nimport org_glassfish_jaxb.jaxb_xjc.jaxb_context_factory_model.ObjectFactory;\\n\", \"newText\": \"import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\\n\"}, {\"oldText\": \"public class JAXBContextFactoryTest {\\n    private static final Class<?> IMPLEMENTATION_OBJECT_FACTORY =\\n            org_glassfish_jaxb.jaxb_xjc.jaxb_context_factory_model.impl.ObjectFactory.class;\\n    private static final String UNSUPPORTED_PROPERTY_NAME = \\\"org.example.unsupportedJaxbProperty\\\";\\n    private static final Map<String, Object> UNSUPPORTED_PROPERTIES = Map.of(UNSUPPORTED_PROPERTY_NAME, Boolean.TRUE);\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void createContextWithClassesLoadsImplementationObjectFactory() {\\n        assertThat(IMPLEMENTATION_OBJECT_FACTORY.getName()).endsWith(\\\".impl.ObjectFactory\\\");\\n\\n        assertThatThrownBy(() -> JAXBContextFactory.createContext(\\n                new Class<?>[] {ObjectFactory.class}, UNSUPPORTED_PROPERTIES))\\n                .isInstanceOf(JAXBException.class)\\n                .hasMessageContaining(UNSUPPORTED_PROPERTY_NAME);\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void createContextWithContextPathLoadsImplementationObjectFactory() {\\n        assertThat(IMPLEMENTATION_OBJECT_FACTORY.getName()).endsWith(\\\".impl.ObjectFactory\\\");\\n\\n        assertThatThrownBy(() -> JAXBContextFactory.createContext(\\n                ObjectFactory.class.getPackageName(),\\n                ObjectFactory.class.getClassLoader(),\\n                UNSUPPORTED_PROPERTIES))\\n                .isInstanceOf(JAXBException.class)\\n                .hasMessageContaining(UNSUPPORTED_PROPERTY_NAME);\\n    }\\n}\\n\", \"newText\": \"public class JAXBContextFactoryTest {\\n    private static final String IMPLEMENTATION_OBJECT_FACTORY = ObjectFactory.class.getPackageName()\\n            + \\\".impl.ObjectFactory\\\";\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void createContextWithClassesLoadsImplementationObjectFactory() {\\n        assertThatExceptionOfType(JAXBException.class)\\n                .isThrownBy(() -> JAXBContextFactory.createContext(new Class<?>[] {ObjectFactory.class}, Map.of()))\\n                .satisfies(exception -> assertThat(exception.getLinkedException())\\n                        .isInstanceOf(ClassNotFoundException.class)\\n                        .hasMessage(IMPLEMENTATION_OBJECT_FACTORY));\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void createContextWithContextPathLoadsImplementationObjectFactory() {\\n        assertThatExceptionOfType(JAXBException.class)\\n                .isThrownBy(() -> JAXBContextFactory.createContext(\\n                        ObjectFactory.class.getPackageName(), ObjectFactory.class.getClassLoader(), Map.of()))\\n                .satisfies(exception -> assertThat(exception.getLinkedException())\\n                        .isInstanceOf(ClassNotFoundException.class)\\n                        .hasMessage(IMPLEMENTATION_OBJECT_FACTORY));\\n    }\\n}\\n\\nfinal class ObjectFactory {\\n    private ObjectFactory() {\\n    }\\n}\\n\"}]}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 448, \"output\": 2835, \"cacheRead\": 30208, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 33491, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1778271374225, \"responseId\": \"resp_0eb0aa1354b923450169fe448efc5c8191bb853a10b9128605\"}}\n../3300-374b5ccf/human-intervention-logs/org.glassfish.jaxb:jaxb-xjc:4.0.6/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-08T20-17-58-138596Z.log:2656:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Exploring ClassLoader Options**\\n\\nI'm considering if both line 84 and line 132 can use ObjectFactory from the same package. For the implementation load, maybe I can use a custom ClassLoader to map the class name `...impl.ObjectFactory` to an existing class. It seems that for line 84, using `c.getClassLoader().loadClass` isn't custom unless the class is loaded by that custom ClassLoader. This could be a useful avenue to explore further!\\n\\n**Evaluating class structure**\\n\\nI'm focusing on adding tests to ensure the execution reaches uncovered dynamic-access call sites. While a ClassNotFoundException (CNFE) is acceptable, it's not the most valuable outcome. I'm considering that \\\"one-to-one mapping\\\" might be a stronger approach. To comply with existing rules, it's better to create just one new Java file, but maybe I can include both in a public package, like ObjectFactory. It seems I can expect CNFE, which could eliminate the need for support files.\\n\\n**Evaluating dynamic access tracking**\\n\\nI'm reflecting on whether a failing load in ClassLoader#loadClass counts as dynamic access. I wonder if the trace agent captures events before and after the loading process. If a load fails, it's likely that no configuration is emitted since the class wasn't loaded in the first place. This leaves me questioning how dynamic access is reported when it comes to errors in loading classes. It seems there's a lot to consider in this scenario!\\n\\n**Considering class issues**\\n\\nI’m thinking about potential context overloads and the expected outcomes. There might be an issue with the support class not being public, which could cause `ClassLoader.loadClass` for the implementation to fail. But do we really need it public? I think it would be better if I edited the setup and removed the support directory altogether. That could simplify things and make the process smoother, right? Let’s go for it.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0eb0aa1354b923450169fe448fc49c8191b1cf0d17d813b215\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp_kSu-07EP4TxnLiBdFHgJ3dUWQvUXtsa6Zr4P68AMeqSch4qQx818bcoR6eWpLybOPNBbFuRTRJsEXTjAf5I5GHBIpRYrmjIK6kcbHL2_MvYw3AnDT6xMAVKt0hvqY3mW2T4bWeapfyUej1J4-7lLLoGGN4yy3HBq_3tBPcV6yUrc-HpVkoypkk6TAbXN7v_iRzLSgVc1MBBdLwW3aRyUYX2ChgUdZkRM8erCQCn9L54NvNTOA-8f8OpTWObvmRuRNshYliPSCbGp8hyGT3oyQVB6ZWkS7lBXWhoogMOAdBPPTwbUgvGrA1VCvOYxrXNjvbxy_7Txezyr8CQaSfF1vZwwLugq4XxywSawt8nVlclHaqZyu1987YhyKrYGaZmSt-Z244eyg2kanU18Bw2njOH7TDuJZG9wU134AUJvsyiAFOBZByBXbr0FTGANNxYwyfVwcZilAlXE3fVCAUD4JjEGfVIIsCk0qQ0TK1Q89auWsr4FwGOhmDAVNwM_ibQjRDul0IC2Od8S6nwUN5TQdqtENwC8iZjyI8Rgqgc0I3OVkLUeU2Q6OxvaDMnrYWd